'''Gunjan Sinha''' is an Indian-American [[entrepreneur]] and [[business executive]]. He is the Executive Chairman of MetricStream. He is also best known as the founder of [[Lycos|WhoWhere?]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Lycos' chief thrives on doing things his way|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HfxOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xhQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3135,4171596&dq=gunjan+sinha&hl=en|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=15 February 1999}}</ref> an internet search engine he sold to [[Lycos]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite news|last=Levy|first=Doug|title=Money not the issue with Net elites|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19990301&id=WKJOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zRQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5709,2499506|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=1 March 1999}}</ref><ref name=TWrisingInfo>{{cite book|last=Salkowitz|first=Rob|title=Young World Rising: How Youth Technology and Entrepreneurship are Changing the World from the Bottom Up|date=2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470644324}}</ref> He is also the co-founder of [[Customer engagement|customer engagement software]] provider [[eGain|eGain Corporation]]. He has served on the board of numerous [[Silicon Valley]] startups including Regalix.

==Early life and education==

Sinha attended the [[Indian Institutes of Technology]] where he earned a B.S. in Computer Science.<ref name=OMBOIM>{{cite news|last=Mitra|first=Sramana|title=Managing Risk: MetricStream Chairman Gunjan Sinha|url=http://www.sramanamitra.com/2012/02/09/managing-risk-metricstream-chairman-gunjan-sinha-part-1/|accessdate=5 May 2014|newspaper=One Million by One Million|date=9 February 2012}}</ref> He went on to attend the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]] where he obtained a M.S. in computer science.<ref name=OLookBusinPay>{{cite news|last=Radhakrishnan-Swami|first=Meenakshi|title=Paying It Forward|url=http://www.outlookbusiness.com/printarticle.aspx?288613|accessdate=5 May 2014|newspaper=Outlook Business|date=7 December 2013}}</ref> He added an M.S. in Industrial Engineering and Engineering Management from Stanford University prior to launching his entrepreneurial career.<ref name=OLookBusinPay/>

==Career==

Prior to founding numerous companies, Sinha spent time as a hardware developer at Olivetti Advanced Technology Center as well as an industry advisor for inDplay, Inc. One of his first business ventures was Parsec Technology Pvt. Ltd., a company he co-founded in 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sengupta|first=Paramita|title=IITians are taking over the tech biz in the US|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-07-28/news/27399457_1_tech-biz-iitians-iit-alumni|accessdate=4 May 2014|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=28 July 2004}}</ref> He launched one of the first internet search engines in 1995.<ref name=TWrisingInfo/> Known as [[Lycos|WhoWhere?]], he served as the company's president until he sold the company to [[Lycos]] in 1998 for $133 million in stock.<ref name=LycosCnet>{{cite news|last=Junnarkar|first=Sandeep|title=Lycos buys WhoWhere|url=http://news.cnet.com/Lycos-buys-WhoWhere/2100-1001_3-214296.html|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=cNet|date=11 August 1998}}</ref> At the time of the sale, Lycos was the 4th most popular website behind [[American Online]], [[Yahoo]], and [[MSN]].<ref name=LycosCnet/> 

After WhoWhere?, Sinha went on to co-found [[eGain|eGain Corporation]], a provider of [[customer engagement]] software. He took the company public on the NASDAQ in 1998 and served as the company's president until 2003 when he joined MetricStream where he still serves as the Executive Chairman. Sinha is on the board of LearnStreet, an online education website for computer programmers.<ref name=RefTEchLearnStree>{{cite news|last=Empson|first=Rip|title=LearnStreet Launches With $1M From Vinod Khosla To Help You Learn How To Build, Test and Push Code|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/11/07/learnstreet-launches-with-1m-from-vinod-khosla-to-teach-you-how-to-build-and-push-code/|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=Tech Crunch|date=7 November 2012}}</ref> Launched in 2012, the company is backed by [[Khosla Ventures]].<ref name=RefTEchLearnStree/> 

Sinha has served on numerous boards, including for various non profits. He serves as Chairman of SiliconIndia Inc., Regalix, and previously for arcadiaOne, Inc. He was appointed to the board of the [[Indo-US Science & Technology Forum]] and previously served as a trustee for the [[University of California, Santa Cruz|University of California Santa Cruz Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mickelson|first=Gwen|title=Meet the new trustees: Gunjan Sinha|url=http://news.ucsc.edu/2010/07/3919.html|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=University of California Santa Cruz|date=6 July 2010}}</ref> He is also a frequent speaker at [[Horasis]], an independent [[think tank]] organization based in [[Zurich]], [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sinha|first=Gunjan|title=How Indian Companies Can Build Global Brands|url=http://thriveonrisk.com/conversations/watch/8/How-Indian-Companies-Can-Build-Global-Brands|publisher=Thrive On Risk|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

==Awards and recognition==

In 2007, Sinha was one of 13 [[Indian Americans]] to be named to the list of ''Outstanding 50 Asian Americans in Business''.<ref>{{cite news|title=13 Indians among top Asian businessmen in US|url=http://www.asianam.org/news_2007_vol_2.htm|accessdate=21 April 2014|newspaper=Indian Abroad via Asianam.org|date=19 July 2007}}</ref> He was also featured as one of the ''50 Most Successful Immigrant Entrepreneurs'' by Silicon India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Outstanding 50 Award|url=http://outstanding50award.com/index.php/info/10|accessdate=5 May 2014|newspaper=Asian American Business Development Center|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004073915/http://outstanding50award.com/index.php/info/10|archivedate=4 October 2014|df=}}</ref> 

